# Task #93 — Inter-cycle pipelining (draft N+1 ‖ verify N)

_Opened 2026-04-24 after Path A + Path B + FA-only re-verify all hit the
same "tree-mode phase deltas poison downstream residuals" structural
dead-end (39aa358). Inter-cycle pipelining is the remaining viable
slow-path-latency lever that doesn't touch FA/RoPE/KV semantics._

## Why this exists

Current DFlash cycle is strictly sequential:

```
seed_N → draft_N (~20-30 ms) → verify_N (~60-80 ms) → commit_N → seed_{N+1} → ...
```

Draft and verify use separate weights (draft is small; verify is target).
They could run in parallel. The blocker is that `seed_{N+1}` is produced
by `verify_N` (it's the `bonus_token` — the target's prediction at the
last committed position).

Pipelining approach: start draft N+1 SPECULATIVELY on a PREDICTED seed
while verify N is still running. When verify N completes and we know the
actual bonus_token:

- If predicted seed == actual seed → keep draft N+1's work. Net save:
  min(draft N+1 time, verify N time) per cycle.
- If predicted seed != actual seed → discard draft N+1 and redo. Net
  cost: wasted draft N+1 time.

Profit when: `prediction_accuracy × draft_time > (1-accuracy) × draft_time`
→ `accuracy > 0.5`.

In practice a naive predictor (use draft N's own argmax at the last
accepted position as the bonus guess) tracks target at ~85-95% on code,
75-90% on prose. Well above the 50% break-even.

## Projected win

- Draft forward: ~20-30 ms (small draft model, MQ4)
- Target verify: ~60-80 ms (full forward on block)
- Parallel overlap: `min(draft, verify) × prediction_accuracy`
- ~20 ms × 0.85 ≈ 17 ms saved per cycle out of ~75 ms cycle time
- **Projected speedup: ~22-28 % across all DFlash modes (linear + DDTree)**

Applied to current 2026-04-24 baseline (27B asym3, 3-run median):

| genre    | current (DFlash linear) | +pipeline | current (DDTree b12) | +pipeline |
|----------|------------------------:|----------:|---------------------:|----------:|
| code     | 160.4 / τ=7.91          | ~200      | 111.7 / τ=6.96       | ~140      |
| prose    |  58.0 / τ=1.91          |  ~70      |  71.8 / τ=4.66       |  ~88      |
| instruct |  51.7 / τ=1.57          |  ~62      |  67.8 / τ=3.85       |  ~83      |

DFlash linear on code with pipelining → ~200 tok/s. DDTree b12 on code
still short of ~200 but much closer to 140.

## Seed prediction strategies

The quality of the seed-prediction oracle determines the win. Ordered
by implementation complexity + expected accuracy:

**P0 — Trivial oracle: use draft's own argmax at last accepted slot**

During draft N's forward, the draft produces logits at every position in
its draft block. The argmax at the LAST accepted position is the draft's
best guess for the NEXT token. Target's bonus_token is target's argmax
at the same position. Draft and target agree on argmax at τ ≈ high, which
is the regime where DFlash shines.

Zero extra compute. Cheap to implement.

Expected accuracy: **~85-95 % on high-τ content** (code), **~75-85 % on
prose**, **~70-80 % on instruct**. Matches draft-target argmax agreement
rate, which is exactly `accept_rate`. For the DFlash-winning regimes
where this optimization matters most, the oracle is already accurate.

**P1 — Cache last-cycle's bonus_token position from draft**

Draft's last-position logits might not land at the "last accepted slot"
depending on how acceptance actually walks. Needs a quick per-cycle
post-accept re-run of draft lm_head at the exact accept boundary.
Slightly more accurate; marginal win over P0.

**P2 — Tiny "bonus predictor" model**

Train a tiny sidecar (even a LUT or small transformer) to predict target's
bonus_token from accept pattern + last accepted tokens. Higher accuracy
at runtime cost. Out of scope unless P0/P1 hit a low ceiling.

**Recommendation: ship P0 first.** Instrument accept rate at the bonus
slot specifically; if it's clearly worse than the claimed 0.85, revisit.

## Scope / design

### Stream layout

Need a second compute stream so draft N+1 runs genuinely concurrent with
verify N. HipBridge's `hip.stream_create()` gives a new stream handle.
Current code uses at most one `active_stream`; we add:

- `draft_stream: Option<HipStream>` — owned by the draft pipeline
- `verify_stream: Option<HipStream>` — owned by the verify pipeline
- Legacy single-stream callers keep working via fallback to null stream

Draft kernels explicitly launched on `draft_stream`. Verify kernels on
`verify_stream`. Cross-stream sync via hipEventRecord + hipStreamWaitEvent
at the specific join points (draft-N+1-completion waits for verify-N
completion, so we know which draft was right).

### Draft-scratch isolation

`DflashScratch` holds per-draft-layer scratch tensors. Running two drafts
concurrently on the same scratch would corrupt state. Options:

1. **Two DflashScratch instances** (one per in-flight draft). Memory cost:
   ~(draft_dim × draft_layers × a few) — small, probably under 100 MB on
   the small draft. Simplest correctness story.
2. Single DflashScratch, time-sliced so draft N+1 starts only AFTER draft
   N's forward is fully COMPLETE on-device (draft N's work enqueued on
   draft_stream in sequence). No extra memory, but loses some concurrency
   with draft N's tail phase.

Start with Option 1. Double-buffer at startup cost; simpler invariants.

### Rollback mechanism

After verify N completes, compare predicted_seed_N+1 against actual
bonus_token_N. If match → draft N+1's work is valid; proceed to verify
N+1 normally using draft N+1's output. If mismatch → discard draft N+1's
device-side state (reset DflashScratch[N+1] lazily; the next real draft
just overwrites it) and run draft N+1 from scratch on actual seed.

Rollback cost: one wasted draft forward. Needs:

- Draft's pre-forward snapshot of DN state if draft has any persistent
  state that would advance (DeltaNet snapshot pattern, mirrors the
  existing `draft_snap: DeltaNetSnapshot` that DFlash already keeps).
- Mechanism to NOT advance KV cache writes from the speculative draft
  (draft doesn't write to target KV cache — it has its own; correct).

### Concurrency-correctness audit checklist

- [ ] Target weights: read-only, safe under concurrent read ✓
- [ ] Draft weights: read-only, safe under concurrent read ✓
- [ ] Target KV cache: written by verify N, NOT read by draft N+1
      (draft uses its own KV). Concurrent OK.
- [ ] Draft KV cache / DN state: each draft instance uses its own
      (DflashScratch option 1). Concurrent OK.
- [ ] GdnTape: written by verify N at tree-node positions. Not read by
      draft N+1. Concurrent OK.
- [ ] hidden_rb: written by verify N at committed positions. Read by
      draft N+1 to seed its forward's "previous accepted hidden" input.
      Potential RACE: verify N writes hidden_rb AFTER draft N+1 already
      read a STALE hidden_rb. Must wait for verify N to produce
      hidden_rb before starting draft N+1.
      → draft N+1 starts AFTER verify N writes hidden_rb for last
      committed position (which happens PARTWAY through verify — target
      per-layer writes happen mid-forward, but the final layer's hidden
      is what draft reads). So draft N+1 can only start after verify N's
      final FA/LA layer completes writing to hidden_rb at the committed
      slots.

Actually: in current code, hidden_rb is written at THE FINAL LAYER of
target (per_token_hidden_out). That happens near the END of verify N's
forward, leaving ~30 % of verify N still running (final-norm + LM head).
So overlap window is only the last ~30 %, not the full verify.

**This shrinks the projected win significantly.** Draft takes ~25 ms.
Post-hidden-rb-write portion of verify is ~20 ms. Overlap = min(25, 20)
× accuracy = ~17 ms saved out of 75 ms cycle time → 22 % speedup.
Still material, but not as fat as the first back-of-envelope.

### Alternative: overlap at a different join point

Instead of "draft N+1 starts after verify N's hidden_rb write", we could
have draft N+1 start immediately using LAST cycle's (cycle N-1's) hidden
state — skipping verify N's contribution entirely. This is WRONG for the
draft's input quality (hidden state is stale by one cycle) but may be
OK-ish given the draft is already a lossy approximation.

This is "Approach X" — draft runs on stale context; τ drops slightly but
overlap is full-cycle. Test empirically before committing.

Measure both strategies; ship the one with better wall-clock.

## Implementation phases

**Phase A — Second stream infrastructure.** Non-behavioral. Add
`draft_stream` + `verify_stream` fields to ModelSlot / speculative
driver. Current callers still use whichever stream. Build + confirm
byte-no-op.

**Phase B — Instrumented seed-prediction oracle.** Add a no-op path that
records draft's last-position argmax before verify starts, then compares
against actual bonus_token post-verify. Log accuracy per cycle. No
actual pipelining yet — just collect data.

**Phase C — Double-buffered DflashScratch.** Allocate two draft
scratches at session init. Per-cycle logic uses a flip-flop index.

**Phase D — Concurrent draft N+1.** Launch draft N+1 on draft_stream
BEFORE verify N completes. Insert hipEventRecord at verify-N's final
hidden_rb write. Insert hipStreamWaitEvent on draft_stream so draft
reads stable hidden_rb.

**Phase E — Rollback on mis-prediction.** On mismatch, re-dispatch draft
on actual seed. Draft-scratch flip-flop already isolates.

**Phase F — Gate pass + bench.** Coherence-gate-dflash + speed-gate. 3-run
medians on code/prose/instruct. Compare to committed baselines.

## Speed / correctness gates

**Correctness**:
- Coherence-gate-dflash must pass unchanged (no token attractors).
- Output with pipelining ON must be coherent on eyeball + token-
  distribution detector.
- Output MAY differ byte-exact from default due to ksplit nondeterminism,
  but must stay within same τ noise band (±10 %).
- Mis-prediction rate in Phase B logging must be < 30 % on all genres
  (accuracy > 70 % → positive-sum on P0 oracle).

**Speed**:
- 27B DFlash linear code: **≥ 180 tok/s** (current 160 → +12 %).
- 27B DFlash linear prose: **≥ 64 tok/s** (current 58 → +10 %).
- 27B DDTree b12-k2 code: **≥ 130 tok/s** (current 112 → +16 %).
- 27B DDTree b12-k2 prose: **≥ 82 tok/s** (current 72 → +14 %).
- If prediction accuracy is high and hidden_rb overlap window is larger
  than I've estimated, real numbers could be higher. If overlap is
  smaller than estimated, targets may slip.

**Regressions to avoid**:
- Single-stream mode (pipelining OFF) must be within ±2 % of pre-change
  perf. Opt-in env gate until gates pass.
- Multi-agent GPU lock: stream creation cost is per-session (paid once),
  so no per-cycle hit on the lock.

## Opt-in env gate

`HIPFIRE_DDTREE_PIPELINE=1` (or similar). Default OFF. Ship phases A-E
as env-gated, flip to on-by-default only after ≥ 5 full-matrix benches
pass all gates.

## Out of scope

- Multi-stream KV cache writes (separate task — current per-layer writes
  to same stream are fine).
- Draft model concurrency beyond N+1 (could pipeline N+2 too, but rare
  incremental value and much higher mis-prediction blast radius).
- Target-side parallelism beyond single-stream verify (different task).
- Cross-arch validation (BC-250, MI300X) — gfx1100 first.

